CHAPTER XXXIV.

1. Vestra decora] The word ‘decus’ is here used in a less precise sense than that which it has Ch. 29, sua quisque de- cora gestantes. Here it means ‘glorious deeds.’ Livy, XXI. 43, uses it in just the same sense, Nemo vestrum est cui non idem ego virtutis spectator ac testis notata temporibus locisque referre sua possim decora.

2. Unam legionem] Sc. the 9th legion. See Oh. 26.

3. Furto noctisJ Sc. an attack made under the cover of night. Curtius, lv. 13, uses the same expression, meae gloriae furtum noctis obstare non patiar.
